I've never been a really serious hacker. I haven't ever had the time or patience really to get down to learn how to program. A bit of BASIC in the days of the Sinclair ZX81 and Acorn; a bit of HTML and CSS when I was first learning how to make my own website and blog (in the days before most of this stuff was done for you!) But never seriously got down to Perl, Python, Ruby and the like (though some of them have been little things I've glanced at from time to time, then wondered if I *really* had a use for them.)

Not a hacker... But I have really loved tinkering and playing with my computer set-up. I've loved Linux rather than Windows, because it's easier to do that kind of tinkering. But back in the day when I first used Linux, there were still too many hardware issues. I built my own computer - installed Linux - then when it updated, it 'broke' the audio and I couldn't find any workaround except to buy a new audio card. In the end I gave up and went over first to Mac and then - when I couldn't afford to replace my MacBook - to a Windows laptop. And even though I now have a whizzy new Asus Zenbook running Windows 10, I am once again playing with and enjoying Linux. It's running on the Acer Inspire I bought originally with Windows installed, then overwrote that with Linux Mint.

I used to blog a lot, but that too has lapsed with the growth of social media sites like Facebook. So why go on paying for web hosting? I've been reading about moving websites and blogs to Dropbox, and more especially to Github. So this is the first full post of the new blog. My old one was called *Storyteller's World*. This one is called *Godspelled*, from my Twitter handle.